    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_0",
      "value": "CD laddering is an investment strategy that involves spreading funds across multiple certificates of deposit (CDs) with different maturity dates. Compared to investing in a single short term CD and rolling it over at maturity, CD laddering provides increased returns while creating access to funds periodically to reinvest or withdraw if funds are needed for an unexpected or planned expense."
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_1",
      "value": "CDs are time deposits that are guaranteed for up to $250,000 per depositor per institution by the U.S. Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC). Because CDs are federally insured, they are considered relatively conservative investments. As a result, they pay a lower interest rate -- stated as an annual percentage yield (APY) -- than non-insured investments such as stocks and bonds."
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_2",
      "value": "This financial tool assumes that the short and medium term CDs are reinvested in the long term CD at maturity, with no changes to the interest rates specified."
